{"id":"1401.4992","submitter":"Vicente Garzo","authors":"Jos\\'e Carlos P\\'erez-Fuentes and Vicente Garz\\'o","title":"Influence of a drag force on linear transport in low-density gases.\n  Stability analysis","comments":"3 figures; to be published in Physica A","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.physa.2014.05.036","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The transport coefficients of a dilute classical gas in the presence of a\ndrag force proportional to the velocity of the particle are determined from the\nBoltzmann equation. The viscous drag force could model the friction of solid\nparticles with a surrounding fluid (interstitial gas phase). First, when the\ndrag force is the only external action on the state of the system, the\nBoltzmann equation admits a Maxwellian solution $f_0(\\mathbf{v},t)$ with a\ntime-dependent temperature. Then, the Boltzmann equation is solved by means of\nthe Chapman-Enskog expansion around the local version of the distribution $f_0$\nto obtain the relevant transport coefficients of the system: the shear\nviscosity $\\eta$, the thermal conductivity $\\kappa$, and a new transport\ncoefficient $\\mu$ (which is also present in granular gases) relating the heat\nflux with the density gradient. The results indicate that while $\\eta$ is not\naffected by the drag force, the impact of this force on the transport\ncoefficients $\\kappa$ and $\\mu$ may be significant. Finally, a stability\nanalysis of the linear hydrodynamic equations with respect to the\ntime-dependent equilibrium state is performed, showing that the onset of\ninstability is associated with the transversal shear mode that could be\nunstable for wave numbers smaller than a certain critical wave number.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Jan 2014 17:26:22 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 19 May 2014 15:17:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-18"}
